	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tepples</b> [ Sat Jan 11, 2014 4:18 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: NES manual creation</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Perhaps I came off too glib in my rush to get out the door. But my point is that you can work on the content and have that ready before you make the formatting final. For example, you can make the manual as an HTML document and then transform it into the paged medium once you decide on a page size.<br /><br />Now about the page size in particular: If you're packaging your game in a plastic case, as with early Genesis games and every console from the PS2 on, the size of the manual slot in the case will dictate the size of your manual. If you're packaging your game in a cardboard box, as with NES, Super NES, late Genesis, and N64 games, you can use any size so long as it fits in the box. Does the instruction manual need to be the same size as the manuals that came with NES games?

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


